Here are three impactful security flaws from the modern OWASP Top 10 list, along with examples of vulnerable PHP code and their respective fixed versions.

1. Injection (A1:2021)

Vulnerable code:
```php
$user = $_POST['username'];
$pass = $_POST['password'];
$sql = "SELECT * FROM users WHERE username = '$user' AND password = '$pass'";
$result = mysqli_query($conn, $sql);
```
Fixed code:
```php
$user = $_POST['username'];
$pass = $_POST['password'];
$sql = "SELECT * FROM users WHERE username = ? AND password = ?";
$stmt = $conn->prepare($sql);
$stmt->bind_param("ss", $user, $pass);
$stmt->execute();
$result = $stmt->get_result();
```
To fix injection flaws, use prepared statements with parameterized queries. This ensures that user inputs are treated as data and not as part of the SQL query.

1. Broken Authentication (A2:2021)

Vulnerable code:
```php
session_start();
if (isset($_POST['username']) && isset($_POST['password'])) {
    $user = $_POST['username'];
    $pass = $_POST['password'];
    // Check if user and password are valid (omitted)
    $_SESSION['logged_in'] = true;
    $_SESSION['username'] = $user;
}
```
Fixed code:
```php
session_start();
session_regenerate_id(); // Regenerate session ID to prevent session fixation
if (isset($_POST['username']) && isset($_POST['password'])) {
    $user = $_POST['username'];
    $pass = $_POST['password'];
    // Check if user and password are valid (omitted)
    $_SESSION['logged_in'] = true;
    $_SESSION['username'] = $user;
}
```
To fix broken authentication, use `session_regenerate_id()` to regenerate the session ID whenever there is a change in the user's authentication state. This helps prevent session fixation attacks.

1. Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) (A7:2021)

Vulnerable code:
```php
$message = $_GET['message'];
echo "Your message: " . $message;
```
Fixed code:
```php
$message = $_GET['message'];
$safe_message = htmlspecialchars($message, ENT_QUOTES, 'UTF-8');
echo "Your message: " . $safe_message;
```
To fix XSS vulnerabilities, use functions like `htmlspecialchars()` to properly encode user-supplied data before displaying it on the page. This prevents malicious code from being executed in the user's browser.

Note that the provided examples are for illustrative purposes only and are not exhaustive. It is essential to have a comprehensive understanding of the OWASP Top 10 vulnerabilities and follow secure coding practices to ensure the security of your PHP applications.
